                                                                                                           SET

Iterable
   |
Collection
   |
------------------------------------------------
|                |               |             |
List             Set            Queue         Deque

❖ A Set is a Collection that does not allow duplicate elements.

➤Key Characteristics
↬No duplicates
↬Allows at most one null element (except TreeSet)
↬No index-based access
↬Order depends on implementation

◉ Types of Set in Java
1.HashSet (Most Common)
★ Features
➣ Does not maintain insertion order
➣ Allows one null
➣ Fastest performance
➣ Uses hashing mechanism

Example 
import java.util.HashSet;
class HashSetExample{
public static void main(String [] args){

HashSet<String> set = new HashSet<>();
set.add("RAM");
set.add("SAM");
set.remove("RAM");
set.add("SAM");   // Duplicate - ignored
set.add(null);     // Allowed
set.add(null);     // Ignored

System.out.println(set.contains("Java"));   // true or false return if present or not
System.out.println(set.size()); //Number of Elements
System.out.println(set.isEmpty());  //Check Set Is Empty or Not
System.out.println(set);
  }
 }


2.LinkedHashSet (Maintains Insertion Order)
★ Features
➣ Maintains insertion order
➣ Slightly slower than HashSet
➣ Allows one null

Example
import java.util.LinkedHashSet;
public class LinkedHashSetExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        LinkedHashSet<Integer> set = new LinkedHashSet<>();

        set.add(10);
        set.add(20);
        set.add(30);
        set.add(10); // Duplicate ignored

        System.out.println(set);
    }
}


3.TreeSet (Sorted Set)
★ Features
➣ Stores elements in sorted (ascending) order
➣ Does not allow null
➣ Slower than HashSet
➣ Uses Red-Black Tree

Example
import java.util.TreeSet;

public class TreeSetExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        TreeSet<Integer> set = new TreeSet<>();

        set.add(50);
        set.add(10);
        set.add(30);
        set.add(20);

        System.out.println(set);
    }
}

Output
[10, 20, 30, 50]

❌ Null Example (Runtime Error)
set.add(null); // NullPointerException

Same Summary Table – Applies to ALL Sets
| Method      | Purpose               |
| ----------- | --------------------- |
| add()       | Insert element        |
| remove()    | Delete single element |
| removeAll() | Delete multiple       |
| removeIf()  | Conditional delete    |
| clear()     | Delete all            |
| contains()  | Check element         |
| size()      | Count                 |
| isEmpty()   | Empty check           |
| retainAll() | Keep common elements  |
| addAll()    | Merge sets            |

HashSet vs LinkedHashSet vs TreeSet
| Feature  | HashSet     | LinkedHashSet | TreeSet     |
| -------- | ----------- | ------------- | ----------- |
| Order    | No          | Insertion     | Sorted      |
| Speed    | Fast        | Medium        | Slow        |
| Null     | One         | One           | Not allowed |
| Use Case | Fast lookup | Order needed  | Sorted data |

IMP 
Q1. Why duplicates are not allowed in Set?
→ Uses equals() and hashCode() to ensure uniqueness.

Q2. Why TreeSet does not allow null?
→ Sorting requires comparison; null cannot be compared.
--- The difference lies only in ordering, performance, and null handling.
